Wisconsin Breast Cancer Dataset : Predicting Diagnosis¶

  • Classification: k-Nearest Neighbors and Logistic Regresion

About the dataset: The data includes diagnosis of the tumor with M meaning cancer (malignant) and B no cancer (benign), and 10 features, describing physical properties of cell nuclei from biopsy samples. Each feature is represented three times, once for mean, once for standard error, and once for the worst values.

# function to create decision regions or grids
 
def decision_region(dataFrame,feature1,feature2):
    """
    Function to plot decision regions.
    Takes in the dataframe with two features a and b.
    Returns the grid for plotting decision boundary.
    """
    x_min,x_max = dataFrame[feature1].min() - 0.1, dataFrame[feature1].max() + 0.1
    y_min,y_max = dataFrame[feature2].min() - 0.1, dataFrame[feature2].max() + 0.1
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(x_min,x_max,100),np.linspace(y_min,y_max,100))  #create a rectangular grid out of an array of x values and an array of y values.
    return xx,yy

# function to plot the decsion boundary
# Takes in the classifier object for the model, the grid for plotting decision bpundary, Target class and two features.
# Plots decision boundary.

def decision_boundary(classifier,training,xx,yy,feature1,feature2,target):
    
    # predicting on the decision region
    yhat = classifier.predict(np.c_[xx.ravel(),yy.ravel()])    # predicting on the grid
    # put the result into color plot
    yhat = yhat.reshape(xx.shape)
    
    cmap_light = ListedColormap(['#FFAAAA', '#AAFFAA', '#AAAAFF'])
    cmap_bold = ListedColormap(['#FF0000', '#00FF00', '#0000FF'])
    
    # To plot the decision boundary, we assign color to each point in the mess
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,9))
    plt.pcolormesh(xx,yy,yhat,cmap=cmap_light)      # x and y are bounds, so yhat should be the value inside those bounds.
    
    # plot the training points also
    plt.scatter(training[feature1],training[feature2],c=target, cmap=cmap_bold,
               edgecolor='k', s=45)
    plt.xlim(xx.min(),xx.max())
    plt.ylim(yy.min(),yy.max())
    plt.title("Classification")
    plt.show()

3.1 k-fold Cross Validation¶
In [44]:
# Function that takes in a dataset and performs nfolds k fold cross validation
# where k = number of folds 
def kFolds_CV(k,data,targetVariable):
    
    indices = np.arange(len(data))
    np.random.shuffle(indices)
    
    # creating/initializing empty containers for storing the values
    results = []
    accuracy =[]                 
    precision = []
    recall = []
    

    for i in range(k):
        itest = indices[i::k]  # go by k 
        itrain = list(set(indices).difference(itest))
        testDat = data.iloc[itest]
        trainDat = data.iloc[itrain]
        #ytestDat = ylog_train.iloc[itest]
        #ytrainDat = ylog_train.iloc[itrain]
        
        Xkf_train = trainDat[trainDat.columns.difference([targetVariable])]    # removing the target variable from training set
        Xkf_test = testDat[testDat.columns.difference([targetVariable])]       # removing the target variable from test set
        ykf_train = trainDat[targetVariable]
        ykf_test = testDat[targetVariable]
        
        logkf_clf = LogisticRegression(C=1).fit(Xkf_train,ykf_train)           # Fitting logistic regression model
        y_predkf = logkf_clf.predict(Xkf_test)
        
        acc = metrics.accuracy_score(ykf_test, y_predkf)                       # Calculating metrics for each fold
        prec = metrics.precision_score(ykf_test,y_predkf)
        rec = metrics.recall_score(ykf_test,y_predkf)
        
        accuracy.append(acc)                                                   # appending the results of each fold to the main list
        precision.append(prec)
        recall.append(recall)
        
        
        print("\n Accuracy Kfold %i :" %(i), acc),  print("Precision Kfold %i :" %(i), prec),  print("Recall Kfold %i :" %(i), rec)
    
    print("\n Mean Accuracy: ",np.mean(accuracy))
    #results.append(np.mean(accuracy))
    #results.append(np.mean(precision))
    #results.append(np.mean(recall))
    #return results

3.2 Regularization¶

def kFolds_CV_Reg(k,data,targetVariable,lam):
    
    indices = np.arange(len(data))
    np.random.shuffle(indices)
    
    results = []
    accuracy =[]
    precision = []
    recall = []
    

    for i in range(k):
        itest = indices[i::k]  # go by k
        itrain = list(set(indices).difference(itest))
        testDat = data.iloc[itest]
        trainDat = data.iloc[itrain]
        #ytestDat = ylog_train.iloc[itest]
        #ytrainDat = ylog_train.iloc[itrain]
        
        Xkf_train = trainDat[trainDat.columns.difference([targetVariable])]      # removing the target variable from training set
        Xkf_test = testDat[testDat.columns.difference([targetVariable])]         # removing the target variable from test set
        ykf_train = trainDat[targetVariable]
        ykf_test = testDat[targetVariable]
        
        # we can tune the value of lambda ; i.e. control the amount of regularization
        logkf_clf = LogisticRegression(C=1/lam).fit(Xkf_train,ykf_train)        # Fitting logistic regression model with 
        y_predkf = logkf_clf.predict(Xkf_test)                                  # Using ridge regularization as penalty='l2', by default 
        
        acc = metrics.accuracy_score(ykf_test, y_predkf)
        prec = metrics.precision_score(ykf_test,y_predkf)
        rec = metrics.recall_score(ykf_test,y_predkf)
        
        accuracy.append(acc)
        precision.append(prec)
        recall.append(recall)
        
        
        #print("\n Accuracy Kfold %i :" %(i), acc),  print("Precision Kfold %i :" %(i), prec),  print("Recall Kfold %i :" %(i), rec)
    
    results.append(np.mean(accuracy))
    results.append(lam)
    return results
